### if-else in C

The `if` statement executes a block of code if a condition is true. The optional `else` block executes when the condition is false.

### Syntax

```c
if (condition) {
  // code if true
} else if (another_condition) {
  // code if another_condition is true
} else {
  // code if all conditions are false
}
```

### Common Mistakes

| Mistake | Why It's Wrong |
|---------|---------------|
| `if (x = 5)` | Assignment `=` instead of comparison `==` |
| Missing braces | Only first statement belongs to if |
| Semicolon after if | `if (x > 5);` ends the condition |
| Using `=` instead of `==` | Changes the variable instead of comparing |

### Nested if-else

You can nest if-else statements inside other if-else statements.

---

> **Key Point:** Always use braces `{}` even for single statements to avoid bugs. Most C style guides enforce this rule.

codeExample:
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  int marks = 85;
  if (marks >= 90) {
    printf("Grade: A\n");
  } else if (marks >= 75) {
    printf("Grade: B\n");
  } else if (marks >= 60) {
    printf("Grade: C\n");
  } else {
    printf("Grade: F\n");
  }
  return 0;
}
